name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Abraham Thomas Lincoln (February 12, 1809 – April 15, 1865) was an American statesman, politician, and lawyer who served as the 16th president of the United States from 1861 until his assassination in April 1865.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln led the nation through the American Civil War, its bloodiest war and its greatest moral, constitutional, and political crisis.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He preserved the Union, abolished slavery, strengthened the federal government, and modernized the U.S. economy.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Born in Kentucky, Lincoln grew up on the frontier in a poor family.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Self-educated, he became a lawyer, Whig Party leader, state legislator and Congressman.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He left government to resume his law practice, but angered by the success of Democrats in opening the prairie lands to slavery, reentered politics in 1854.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He became a leader in the new Republican Party and gained national attention in 1858 for debating and losing to national Democratic leader Stephen A. Douglas in a Senate campaign.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He then ran for President in 1860, sweeping the North and winning.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Southern pro-slavery elements took his win as proof that the North was rejecting the Constitutional rights of Southern states to practice slavery.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: They began the process of seceding from the union.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: To secure its independence, the new Confederate States of America fired on Fort Sumter, one of the few U.S. forts in the South.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln called up volunteers and militia to suppress the rebellion and restore the Union.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: As the leader of the moderate faction of the Republican Party, Lincoln confronted Radical Republicans, who demanded harsher treatment of the South; War Democrats, who rallied a large faction of former opponents into his camp; anti-war Democrats (called Copperheads), who despised him; and irreconcilable secessionists, who plotted his assassination.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln fought the factions by pitting them against each other, by carefully distributing political patronage, and by appealing to the American people.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: His Gettysburg Address became an iconic call for nationalism, republicanism, equal rights, liberty, and democracy.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He suspended habeas corpus, and he averted British intervention by defusing the Trent Affair.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln closely supervised the war effort, including the selection of generals and the naval blockade that shut down the South's trade.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: As the war progressed, he maneuvered to end slavery, issuing the Emancipation Proclamation of 1863; ordering the Army to protect escaped slaves, encouraging border states to outlaw slavery, and pushing through Congress the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which outlawed slavery across the country.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln managed his own re-election campaign.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He sought to reconcile his damaged nation by avoiding retribution against the secessionists.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: A few days after the Battle of Appomattox Court House, he was shot by John Wilkes Booth, an actor and Confederate sympathizer, on April 14, 1865, and died the following day.
entities_list: the Battle of Appomattox Court House

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Abraham Lincoln is remembered as the United States' martyr hero.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He is consistently ranked both by scholars and the public as among the greatest U.S. presidents.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence:
Family and childhood
Early life
Abraham Lincoln was born on February 12, 1809, as the second child of Thomas and Nancy Hanks Lincoln, in a one-room log cabin on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He was a descendant of Samuel Lincoln, an Englishman who migrated from Hingham, Norfolk, to its namesake Hingham, Massachusetts, in 1638.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Samuel's grandson and great-grandson began the family's westward migration, passing through New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Virginia.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln's paternal grandfather and namesake, Captain Abraham Lincoln, moved the family from Virginia to Jefferson County, Kentucky, in the 1780s.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Captain Lincoln was killed in an Indian raid in 1786.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: His children, including eight-year-old Thomas, Abraham's father, witnessed the attack.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Thomas then worked at odd jobs in Kentucky and in Tennessee, before settling with members of his family in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln's mother, Nancy, is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks, although no record documents this.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, in Washington County, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: They produced three children: Sarah, born on February 10, 1807; Abraham, on February 12, 1809; and Thomas, who died in infancy.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Thomas Lincoln bought or leased farms in Kentucky.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Thomas became embroiled in legal disputes, and lost all but 200 acres (81 ha) of his land in court disputes over property titles.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where the survey process was more reliable and land titles were more secure.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Indiana was a "free" (non-slaveholding) territory, and they settled in an "unbroken forest" in Hurricane Township, Perry County.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: (Their land became part of Spencer County, Indiana, when the county was established in 1818.)

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In 1860, Lincoln noted that the family's move to Indiana was "partly on account of slavery", but mainly due to land title difficulties.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He owned farms, town lots and livestock, paid taxes, sat on juries, appraised estates, served on country slave patrols, and guarded prisoners.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptists church, which forbade alcohol, dancing, and slavery.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas eventually obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) of land in what became known as the Little Pigeon Creek Community.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: On October 5, 1818, Nancy Lincoln died of milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of a household that included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Dennis Hanks, Nancy's 19-year-old orphaned cousin.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Those who knew Lincoln later recalled that he was distraught over his sister's death on January 20, 1828, while giving birth to a stillborn son.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: On December 2, 1819, Thomas married Sarah "Sally" Bush Johnston, a widow from Elizabethtown, Kentucky, with three children of her own.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Abraham became close to his stepmother, whom he referred to as "Mother".

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln disliked the hard labor associated with farm life.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He was called lazy for all his "reading, scribbling, writing, ciphering, writing Poetry, etc.".

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: His stepmother acknowledged he did not enjoy "physical labor", but loved to read.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln was largely self-educated.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: His formal schooling (from itinerant teachers) was intermittent, totaling less than 12 months; however, he was an avid reader and retained a lifelong interest in learning.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Family, neighbors, and schoolmates recalled that he read and reread the King James Bible, Aesop's Fables, John Bunyan's The Pilgrim's Progress, Daniel Defoe's Robinson Crusoe, Mason Locke Weems's The Life of Washington, and The Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin, among others.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Teenaged Lincoln took responsibility for chores.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He accepted the customary practice that a son give his father all earnings from work outside the home until age 21.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln became adept at using an axe.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Tall for his age, Lincoln was strong and athletic.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He became known for his strength and audacity after winning a wrestling match with the renowned leader of a group of ruffians known as "the Clary's Grove boys".

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In early March 1830, partly out of fear of a milk sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family moved west to Illinois, a free state, and settled in Macon County, 10 miles (16 km) west of Decatur.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Historians disagree on who initiated the move; Thomas Lincoln had no obvious reason to do so.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: One possibility is that other members of the family, including Dennis Hanks, might not have matched Thomas's stability and steady income.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: After the family relocated to Illinois, Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part because of his father's lack of education, although occasionally lending him money.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In 1831, as Thomas and other family prepared to move to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, Abraham left home.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He lived in New Salem for six years.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln and some friends took goods by flatboat to New Orleans, where he witnessed slavery firsthand.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence:
Marriage and children
According to some sources, Lincoln's first romantic interest was Ann Rutledge, whom he met when he first moved to New Salem; these sources indicate that by 1835, they were in a relationship but not formally engaged.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: She died on August 25, 1835, most likely of typhoid fever.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In the early 1830s, he met Mary Owens from Kentucky.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Mary if she returned to New Salem.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Mary arrived in November 1836, and Lincoln courted her for a time; however, they both had second thoughts.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: On August 16, 1837, Lincoln wrote Mary a letter suggesting he would not blame her if she ended the relationship.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: She never replied.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In 1840, Lincoln became engaged to Mary Todd, a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy slave-owner in Lexington, Kentucky.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: They met in Springfield, Illinois in December 1839 and were engaged a year later.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: A wedding set for January 1, 1841, was canceled at Lincoln's initiative.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: They reconciled and married on November 4, 1842, in the Springfield mansion of Mary's married sister.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: While anxiously preparing for the nuptials, Lincoln was asked where he was going and replied, "To hell, I suppose."

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near Lincoln's law office.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Mary kept house, often with the help of a relative or hired servant.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He was an affectionate, though often absent, husband and father of four children.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Robert Todd Lincoln was born in 1843 and Edward Baker Lincoln (Eddie) in 1846.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Edward died on February 1, 1850, in Springfield, probably of tuberculosis.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: "Willie" Lincoln was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever on February 20, 1862.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: The Lincolns' fourth son, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of heart failure at the age of 18 on July 16, 1871.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Robert reached adulthood and produced children.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: The Lincolns' last descendant, great-grandson Robert Todd Lincoln Beckwith, died in 1985.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln "was remarkably fond of children", and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: The deaths of their sons had profound effects on both parents.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Abraham suffered from "melancholy", a condition later referred to as clinical depression.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Later in life, Mary struggled with the stresses of losing her husband and sons, and Robert committed her temporarily to a mental health asylum in 1875.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln's father-in-law and others of the Todd family were either slave owners or slave traders.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln was close to the Todds, and he and his family occasionally visited them.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Mary cooked for Lincoln often during his presidency.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Raised by a wealthy family, her cooking was simple, but satisfied Lincoln's tastes, which included imported oysters.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence:
Early career and militia service
In 1832 Lincoln and partner Denton Offutt bought a general store on credit in New Salem, Illinois.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and Lincoln eventually sold his share.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: That March he entered politics, running for the Illinois General Assembly, advocating navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He could draw crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked an education, powerful friends, and money and lost the election.

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: Lincoln interrupted his campaign to briefly serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia (during the Black Hawk War).

name: AbrahamLincoln.txt
sentence: He then returned to his campaign.
